definition.value: A penicillinate anion formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy function of benzylpenicilloyl-butylamine.
A member of the class of 4'-methoxyisoflavones that is formononetin with a hydroxy group at the 2'position.
An olefinic fatty acid that is octanoic acid carrying a double bond at position 5 (the 5Z-isomer).
An L-proline derivative that is L-proline substituted by a carboxymethyl group at position 3 and a 6-carboxyhepta-2,5-dien-2-yl group at position 4. It is isolated from the red alga, Chondria armata.

Any member of a group of vitamers that belong to the chemical structural class called butenolides that exhibit biological activity against vitamin C deficiency in animals. The vitamers include L-ascorbic acid and its salt, ionized and oxidized forms.
A tertiary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of setiptiline obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
The organic sodium salt of the (5R,6R)-benzylpenicilloyl-butylamine conjugate.
A maleate salt obtained by reaction of setiptiline with one equivalent of maleic acid.
A secondary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of dizocilpine obtained by protonation of the secondary amino group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A maleate salt obtained by reaction of dizocilpine with one equivalent of maleic acid.
Cobamide in which 5-hydroxy-1H-benzimidazole is attached by a glycosyl link from its N-1 to the C-1 of the ribose moiety.
An organic cationic group that is the univalent group derived from trimethylammonium by removal of a hydrogen atom.
An inorganic sodium salt composed of a sodium cation and an azanide anion. It is used as a strong base in organic synthesis.
A 3-hexene in which the double bond adopts a cis-configuration.
A terminal acetylenic compound that is hexane carrying a triple bond at position 1.
A member of the class of hydroquinones that is hydroquinone substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 3 and 5.
A pyridinium salt having chlorochromate as the counterion. It is used as an oxidizing agent to convert primary and secondary alcohols to aldehydes and ketones respectively.
A pyridinium salt that is the dipyridinium salt of dichromic acid. It is a strong oxidizing agent which can convert primary and secondary alcohols to aldehydes and ketones respectively.
A composition-only glycan consisting of six hexosyl groups, two acetaminohexosyl groups and one 6-deoxy-hexosyl group (identities and connectivity unknown). Composition: Hex6 HexNAc2 dHex1.
A composition-only glycan consisting of six hexosyl groups and four acetaminohexosyl groups (identities and connectivity unknown). Composition: Hex6 HexNAc4.
A composition-only glycan consisting of one 6-deoxyhexosyl group (identities and connectivity unknown). Composition: dHex1.
An alkene that is hexane carrying a double bond at position 3.
A 3-hexene in which the double bond adopts a trans-configuration.

An amino disaccharide epitope consisting of two N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues linked (1->2). Its coupling with the carrier protein CRM197 via the DAS linker results in a neoglycoconjugate which has been used in investigations into vaccine development against brucellosis.
A double charged organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of presqualene monophosphate. Major species at pH 7.3.

A polysaccharide derivative consisting of beta-D-glucopyranosyl residues linked (1->3), with approximately 20% of the residues carrying a carboxymethyl substituent at O-6. A soluble/gelatinous substrate for the assay of endo-1,3-beta-D-glucanase.
An alpha-bergamotene that has cis-configuration. It can either be the (1R,5R,6R)-isomer or the (1S,5S,6S)-isomer.
A benzenetriol that is benzophenone in which one of the phenyl groups is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2, 3, and 4. It is a redox mediator.
